data.content:
Yes! Modern MSTest (v3.4+) supports **tuple-based `DynamicData`**, which gives you compile-time type safety instead of `object[]`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:** `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>`. The tuple elements are matched to test method parameters by position, and any type mismatch is now a compile-time error.

For simple constants like this, `[DataRow]` is even more concise:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

Use **tuples** when your data is computed or complex; use **`[DataRow]`** when all values are compile-time constants.
